charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Today is a very special day because it marks 11 years since my dear grandfather passed to Cancer. To me, he was more than just my grandfather, he was my best friend and the reason for the man I have become today. I learned more from my grandfather than I did from my own parents, he truly inspired me. Most of my deepest passions he weaved into me at a young age, Music, Creative design, and a will to always fight for what you believe in no matter the cost!

Thank you for taking the time to hear my story.

story:
Thanks for supporting Macmillan Cancer Support through the Annual Christmas Raffle for colleagues. 

Please ensure that your full name and donation amount are visible (do not make these anonymous), and that you provide an email address or contact number in your message so that we can contact you if you have won.

Any donations made after midday on Monday 21st December will not be counted in the raffle draw but all monies will still go directly to Macmillan.

Macmillan is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. So whatever cancer throws your way, we’re right right there with you. Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Over our mothers short time of illness with terminal cancer the support that my mother received from the Harrogate Hospital and Harrogate Community Palliative care team was astounding.

The thoughtfulness of the situation and sheer determination to control mums symptoms was so expertly considered and delivered. My brother and I cannot thank you enough for this. The work you do is truly amazing, and thank you so much. A special thank you to Charlotte and Hannah you understood my Mum and looked after her accordingly ;-) xxx

eventName: A Mile a Day for Macmillan
story: After a shocking 2020, I’ll be starting 2021 right by attempting to run a mile every day for the month of January in the hopes of raising some money for Macmillan. We lost my wee gran to cancer in May 2018, so I’m honoured to be able to do this in her memory. After my dad and brother both fundraising for Cancer Research UK in September, I thought I’d follow in their footsteps, this time for Macmillan because of their amazing care for my gran. As most of you may know, I’m not a great runner (even after my short phase in lockdown) so we’ll start with a mile a day, let’s see where I end up!

The nation’s leading first aid charity.

Our volunteers provide first aid in their communities and thanks to them fewer lives will be lost needlessly. 
Raise money. Help save lives. Be the difference.
charity.name: St John Ambulance
story:
As a charity with a long history of serving humanity, we are proud of our past, our role in the pandemic and excited about creating a healthier, safer, brighter and more resilient future.

This winter may be our toughest yet and I am helping to bring some community spirit by sharing my sparkle by supporting St John. 

St John volunteers treat and transport thousands of patients each year, and in times of crisis we are England's national health reserve.  

During the pandemic our skilled and highly trained volunteers are working long shifts supporting sick people and their families, in hospitals, in ambulances and at home. We are proud to be working alongside the nations ambulance trusts and in hospitals around the country.

"I enjoy helping people and its what I have been training to do. Its very rewarding personally knowing that my colleagues and I are making a difference to peoples lives when they most need it." 
Tom Willis, volunteer 

Will you support me and help make a difference?

On 22 December 2020 Simon Long, John Munday, Rob Simpson, James Onions, Ashley Hoppley and Tom Clayton will be undertaking a relay attempt to cycle the equivalent elevation of Everest (8,848m) in a day.

Described by Everesting cc as:

'FIENDISHLY SIMPLE, YET BRUTALLY HARD.
EVERESTING IS THE MOST DIFFICULT
CLIMBING CHALLENGE IN THE WORLD'

Our attempt will be undertaken on Zwift on the virtual Alpe dHuez in the French Alps (12.2km @ 8.5%).

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thought I would give this a go, along with several other Imps!

Something that is personally very close to me.

Dad had his first serious heart attack at 50, followed by several others and TIA's. He had to stop working due to ill health several years before retirement. He had a stent, pacemaker and difribilator fiitted to allow him to have a reasonable standard of life again.

My Grandad also had heart problems and suffered with angina for many years.

Just under 2 years ago, a close friend and fellow Imp from Sleaford, suffered a major heart attack. He is gradually making progress and beginning to enjoy life again. 

Go The Distance .100 Km . For your health ;for the challenge ;for the cause.Becoming a BHF Champion and improving health and well being and welcoming 2021 with new healthy habits .Thank you so much to everyone that has signed up so far its been a fantastic effort .Please do join our strava group also https://www.strava.com/clubs/gothedistance100k .

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

Jean passed away on 5 Dec 2020, aged 93, following several health problems including atrial fibrillation and a few months ago, a stroke. For most of her long life she remained in good health and spirits, bringing up her children in a loving home, in a way that was always gentle, nurturing and caring.

Your donation to the British Heart Foundation is something that would warm her heart as well as help repair the hearts of others with life still to live.

story:
We want to challenge our entire team to make a healthy start to 2021 by taking on a charity step challenge through the month of January.

Its roughly 850 or so miles from Blackfriars to Barcelona, which if we get moving as teams should see us in arrive in Barcelona by the end of January. 

Not only is this important and a good idea from a health and wellbeing perspective, but it’s a great opportunity to raise some money for charity. It’s been a really difficult year for a lot of charities given the cancellation of so many huge public events that normally generate large amounts of donations. So, I think it would be a really positive start to the year if we take some action ourselves and contribute just a little bit between us.

eventName: Middle Street Secret Santa - Guide Dogs
story:
Help us raise enough to support 12 brand new guide dogs this Christmas! 

During December hundreds of our fundraising dogs across the UK would usually be out and about wagging their tails and meeting you at supermarket and street collections, Christmas fairs and festive coffee mornings. Our four-legged fundraisers support the 400+ fundraising groups across the UK from Glasgow to Plymouth and everywhere in between.

Due to the current situation, most of our fundraising groups will not be out collecting this festive season, and our four-legged fundraisers will be very much missed! We hope you will do your bit and help us as we aim to raise enough for 12 new guide dog partnerships! Heres how you can join in: 

	Donate £12 and share our posts across social media nominating a friend, family member or colleague to  get involved

	Set up your own fundraiser on this page

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit.

People who knew our mum might not believe but she was very keen to leave a legacy to Guide Dogs. However, her eyesight was diminishing rapidly and despite her many protestations, she really did love Molly the Jug.

We were as surprised as anyone else when she first mentioned it as she'd never really shown much interest in dogs. In fact, she refused to babysit for Rhiannon's dogs because of the farting and snoring!

So along with The Alzheimer's Society (see link below to this page), we'd love to support Guide Dogs.

https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tovey-bros27

Thank you so much for your donation.

Hawys, Rhiannon, Tim, Menna and Osian

story:
This year our Christmas productions are very different as we couldn’t invite our families  into school to watch our performances due to the Covid restrictions.

 We all really hope you have enjoyed our online alternative! 

We are still keen to try to raise some money to help with worthwhile causes like we have done in previous years. We can’t collect money on the day but hope you will feel able to donate after watching our performance online. 

As a class we discussed different problems we wanted to do something about. There were so many ideas and charities that we wanted to support but after a lot of thought, we chose Guide dogs as our charity.

Below is more information from the Guide dog’s Christmas appeal : 

Help us raise enough to support 12 brand new guide dogs this Christmas! story:
Since being a child, I’ve always watched the London Marathon and wanted to give it a go, in fancy dress of course, but with a bad back I’ve been nervous at the thought of pounding the hard pavements training. With sitting constantly at a desk, then the sofa in front of the TV at night during Covid I feel my body has now started to rust, so therefore I wanted to set a challenge to motivate me to get moving again, and also stop me eating all the Christmas food in the house!

My friend Rachael was due to run the London landmarks half marathon 2020 but due to Covid it was delayed until May 2021. She will claim she had no part in this, but having planted the seed saying you can run in fancy dress and they provide the suit… After careful consideration (all of 5 minutes) knowing I currently can’t run more than 2 miles without stopping and needing help putting on my socks the next day, I foolishly signed up!

Now 13 miles might not seem far for most, I know a lot of people who run this distance every week if not more, but this is far for me! It’s fair to say the only time you will ever see me smiling while running is when I’m chasing after the ice-cream van for my 99er.

I will be running for guide dogs and will be dressed as a big dog. I’m hoping (and aware I sound like the TV adverts) if everyone can spare just £1, I should be able hit my minimum target. And I really am hoping to hit this target because I didn’t bother reading the small print!

Every hour, another person in the UK goes blind. Almost two million people in the UK are living with sight loss, and 180,000 of those rarely leave their home alone. This charity relies on our donations to continue their life-changing work. Every pound raised does make a difference to people in the UK. My sponsorship will help sponsor puppies from 6 weeks to becoming a fully-qualified guide dog after 24 months of training, and will help give freedom and independence to people with sight loss.

I started my couch to 5k yesterday (14/12/20), and will continue my training up to April to ensure I do not let you or the charity down, and please don’t worry if you see me running down the street in my onesie
come March 2021, I’m ok and just training / preparing for the extra costume weight, I’ve not lost my mind…

I understand the past year has been incredibly hard financially for everyone and I’m conscious of my timing. However, I’m hoping, dressed in a heavy, sweaty dog suit it will encourage people to donate any spare change and sponsor me.

Thanks for reading this far

charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
In the UK today, almost two million people are living with sight loss and of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone. Many suffer from depression and struggle with feelings of isolation.

Guide Dogs is here to help solve this problem. We provide individual support that overcomes the emotional and physical challenges faced by people living with sight loss.

We work for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life. We work for a world where blind people no longer feel invisible, where the quality of their eye sight is genuinely the only difference between them and the rest of society.

A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling your needs and dreams. A world where being blind or partially sighted isn't what defines you.

It's quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the Give Now button!

story:
I/We would like to celebrate Oliver`s first year of continuing good health after his bone marrow transplant at Great Ormond Street Hospital(GOSH)on Dec.18 2020. The monies Team Oliver raises will go towards helping other children to receive very expensive,specialist care ,research and support to very worried parents who`s loved ones have life threatening conditions.All charities have suffered during these difficult times so we thank you in advance for any support.

My last big challenge will be to cycle 200+ miles to Paris in July. In the mean time other friends and family will be organising other fund raising events for Team Oliver.

This is my last big challenge ,cycling 200 miles to Paris. In the mean time family and friends will be organising other fund raising events.

story: Thanks for visiting our page. In memory of our lovely colleague Mark, who we lost in 2020, a team of us from IT and FM in the Office for Students are walking, running, rowing, cycling and dancing the 7,284 virtual miles from the Bristol City ground to the football stadium in Guangzhou, China, (one of Bristol's twin cities), to raise money for Cancer Research and St Peter's Hospice.  There are two pages, one for each charity so please pick the one you'd like but we'd like to balance the donations to the two if we can.  Thank you for donating.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I am taking part in a white collar MMA event to raise money for Cancer research UK.

Cancer has affected my family quite massively and is something that has always been on the back of my mind, whether you have lost someone close or you yourself have been affected by this disease, Chances are cancer has impacted someone you know.

Cancer research are one of the leading researchers into new clinical trials and looking for the cures! Every donation no matter how big or small will help find their amazing research and you'd be doing a great thing for an amazing charity.

Whether you donate here, buy the tickets to upcoming event or even share this page is be forever grateful, let's beat cancer :)

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

story:
Hi everybody!

For those of you who may not know me, I am Agnese. This coming summer, I will be climbing Mt Kilimanjaro. A group of university students, and myself, have decided to embark on this journey to raise funds for the Marie Curie Foundation. 

Marie Curie specializes in end of life charity. They provide nursing and hospice care, a free support line and information to help those dealing with death. During these hard times, Marie Curie Nurses have been on the frontline of the COVID-19 pandemic. They have continued to provide care to people living with terminal illness as well as their family members. By supporting this fundraiser in any way, you are making a difference by paying for a nurse to care for a person in need. 

Thank you to everyone for the support! If you can, please feel free to share this page with other members of your community.

Thank you,

Agnese

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
The RNLI Torbay Lifeboat Fundraising Team (TLF) work throughout the year to raise funds to support the RNLI and the two Torbay lifeboats, which serve all 3 towns within Torbay -Torquay, Paignton and Brixham.

There has been a Lifeboat Station in Torbay since 1866 and we currently have 2 lifeboats, the All Weather Severn (ALB) named Alec and Christina Dykes and the Inshore Lifeboat Class D (ILB) named ‘Leslie and Mary Dawes’, covering a coastal area from Teignmouth to Start Bay.  Our Station is one of the busiest in the country and can anticipate approximately 100 launches in any one year.  Brixham is a busy fishing port with Paignton and Torquay central to a large coastal tourist area. Overall, there are five large marinas within our operational area together with leisure and yacht clubs, all manner of water sports as well as cliffs (climbing, walking – and falls!)

An ALB Station costs in excess of £215,000 a year to run so TLF's fundraising is vital to support RNLI operations.

For more information on Torbay Lifeboat and our fundraising
events head to - http://www.torbaylifeboat.co.uk/

eventName: Vobster Festive Fundraiser in aid of the RNLI
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit the Vobster Quay festive fundraiser JustGiving page in aid of the Royal National Lifeboat Institute (RNLI).

Vobster Quay has always been a big supporter of the RNLI and have raised over £30,000 for this worthy charity through our annual festive Vobster Santas sponsored diving event. Since the event’s inception in 2007, Vobster Santas has become the biggest and best charity Santa diving event in the world! We're also the holder of the WORLD RECORD for the most Santa divers in the water at once!

Sadly COVID has forced us to hang up our Santa hats but that doesn't mean that the fundraising has to stop! This year we're hoping to raise £1000 for the RNLI through online donations so dig deep and do your bit! Let's show the RNLI how much we appreciate them this festive season.

Learn more on our facebook page at https://www.facebook.com/vobsterquay/

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
Thank you visiting my Just Giving page. RNLI lifeboats in Northern Ireland protect hundreds of communities through our 24-hour search and rescue service. They rely on the safest, most reliable lifeboats and modern stations to launch from. The RNLI relies on donations from you to continue saving lives at sea and on inland waters - your donation to this page will help support the running of lifeboat stations in Northern Ireland.
So this year.......a different life as we know it, wearing masks, washing hands every two minutes, social distancing and no hugs 😨 But, we have to do our best to look after everyone and keep doing it for as long as is needed. The Turkey Trot will most definitely be happening in 2020 but it too will be different. No big crowds, no indoor tea and cake afterwards, no team runs but  my individual trots. Still there, but different. So I need a good cause.
Most people know that I love a swim in the sea and thankfully it is one activity we have been allowed to continue. I gain so much from being in the water, it hashelped so much with my grief, lonliness reduce stress, helps me sleep, it is exhilarating and makes me happy and you'll always hear me in the water singing.. I feel better inside and out because of it. This summer our local beaches were unbelievably busy and there are a group of people I am so grateful to for looking out for us in the water, the RNLI Lifeguards. This summer they made an unprecedented number of rescues on a daily basis, difficult under normal circumstances but made even more complicated while trying to maintain all the COVID-19 measures. I am so grateful to them and that is why I would love to make the @RNLI Livesavers Fund Northern Ireland my chosen charity for my Turkey Trot donation this year.

Thank You So Much.

Fiona Turkey Trotter.

eventName: In memory of Golestan Shafiq (Nee Shakarchi)
story:
Golestan Shafiq (born Golestan Shakarchi) beloved wife, mother, grandmother and dearest friend passed away peacefully at her home in Kingston, Surrey, surrounded by her family in the early hours of Monday 14th December 2020. 

Golestan had a large and generous heart and filled our lives with love, warmth and laughter. We will miss her dearly. 

Unfortunately, due to the current Covid-19 crisis we will not be able to invite family and friends to the funeral nor hold a Fatiha at our home at this time as we would have wished for her. Instead we would like to invite family and friends to join us in praying for her at her burial tomorrow at 2pm (UK time) on Wednesday 16th December 2020, and to make a donation in her name for any sum no matter how small.

Allah yirhamha. May her soul rest in eternal heavenly peace with God.

charity.name: Unicef UK
story:
Hi Folks

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

With the aim of ending 2020 on a high, I have signed myself up to another charity challenge to push myself and try to raise a few £s for some worthy causes.

Over the years my wonderfully generous friends, family and colleagues have given me plenty of encouragement and given financial support to various charities that has made a real difference to people’s lives. I am kindly asking you to do the same this year.

This year there’s been a few cancelled events, but one that I was signed up for has gone virtual which made the logistics of training and participation a lot easier….

I aim to complete 25,000m of swimming before the year is out. Any venue is allowed, but obviously there’s a preference for indoor and heated! I even get a medal if I complete it, from the folks at https://www.marathonswims.com/

One of the UK tax registered charities that I have chosen to request your financial support for is Unicef to whom a donation means you really are making a difference to children’s lives. From a life-saving vaccine to school books in a rural village classroom, the money you donate today could protect a child from dangers like disease and abuse, and help them grow up safe and healthy.

Their web address is: 

https://www.unicef.org.uk/

charity.description: Médecins Sans Frontières / Doctors Without Borders (MSF) is the world's leading medical humanitarian aid organisation. We work in over 70 countries - in conflict zones, natural disasters and epidemics. We are independent, neutral and impartial. We provide medical care where it's needed most.
charity.name: Medecins Sans Frontieres / Doctors Without Borders (MSF)
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

As a doctor, I have huge admiration for  the medical humanitarian work by MSF. The coronavirus pandemic this year 2020 has highlighted the importance of thinking globally about health and the need for global humanitarian and medical intervention and cooperation.

I would like to support their cause by selling masks which I have home sewn during the long hours of isolation during the covid 19 pandemic.

My masks are designed so they can be fitted over the head and the elastic can be adjusted with a toggle for fit snug behind the neck. I also included a professional flat aluminium nose wire which can be removed. This makes them more suitable for people wearing specs, turbans, headscarfs, hearing aids etc...

I had started sewing masks for family and friends and made gifts to some colleagues, who liked them so much that they ordered more off me to pass on to their friends. Interest grew and some of my masks have since also been sold via a few local businesses for £10-12 each. This allowed me to recuperate the cost for and buy additional materials and expand the project and range of designs and my aim now is to raise money for MSF by "selling" masks via donataions through this website.

Please help me raise funds for MSF by "buying" one of my masks via making a donation on this site. All the proceeds will go directly to MSF if you donate thought this site. For those who cannot collect the mask in person, I will happily post out to you within the UK and EU.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story: I am challenging myself to drink nothing but water this January. I am taking on the ultimate detox by avoiding caffeine, alcohol and all other drinks while supporting WaterAid. Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in communities across Ethiopia. Together, we will bring clean water to 50,000 people in Ethiopia and thousands more around the world, helping them change their own lives, forever. If you would like further information about the difference your gift will make and the positive impact it will have on peoples lives, please visit us at www.wateraid.org/uk
